nts infuse the governmental practices of Taiwanese bureaucrats charged with regulating immigration and producing citizenship and sovereignty. Its attention to a group of immigrants whose exceptional status has become necessary to Taiwan’s national integrity exposes the social, political, and subjective consequences of life on the margins of citizenship and sovereignty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChinesezTaiwanxSocial conditions. 0aCitizenshipzTaiwan. 0aForeign spouseszTaiwanxSocial conditions. 0aIntercountry marriagexPolitical aspectszTaiwan. 0aSelf-determination, NationalzTaiwan. 0aWomen immigrantszTaiwanxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aasian studies.  achina.  achinese history.  achinese marital immigrants.  achinese spouses.  acitizenship.  acold war asia.  acontemporary politics in asia.  afemale chinese immigrants.  afemale emigrants from china.  aforeign spouses taiwan.  aimmigrant chinese women.  aimmigration china to taiwan.  aimmigration.  aintercountry marriage.  amarital immigration.  amarriage and family china.  amarriage and family taiwan.  amarrying to immigrate.  ataiwan.  ataiwanese citizenship.  ataiwanese immigration.  ataiwanese sovereignty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028622140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096156240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961562423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961562/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY